\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. E. nigrum} L.,{\i  Sp. Pl.} 1022 (1753). Stems procumbent to ascending; young twigs minutely glandular-puberulent, soon glabrous. Leaves 3-7 × 1-2 mm, linear-oblong to narrowly elliptical, glandular when young, glabrous later; margins closely approximated but not or only slightly involute, whitish, so that the apparent abaxial surface of the leaf bears a pale stripe or shallow groove. Sepals and petals c. 1·5 mm, oblong, greenish pink to reddish-purple. Stamens up to 5 mm, long-exserted. Stigma sessile, with 6-9 rays. Drupe 5 mm in diameter, black.{\i  Heaths, moors, coniferous forests and stony mountain-slopes. N. Europe, and on mountains southwards to the Pyrenees, C. Italy, Bulgaria and S. Ural.} Al Au Be Br Bu Cz Da Fa Fe Ga Ge Hb He Ho Hs Is It Ju No Po Rm Rs (N, B, C, W) Sb Su.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  The genus consists of a number of closely related taxa (for the most part American) which are variously treated as species, subspecies or varieties. The two European taxa, here treated as subspecies, are often regarded as separate species, largely because of their difference in chromosome number; but the correlation between chromosome number and reproductive pattern, though good, is not perfect (the latter being possibly susceptible to environmental influences), and the differences in vegetative characters show some overlap.
\par 

\par 

\pard\f0\fs28   ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b nigrum}: Normally dioecious. Stems up to 120 cm, procumbent, sparingly branched, usually rooting; leaves mostly linear-oblong, 2½-5 times as long as wide, usually not grooved beneath. 2n = 26.{\i  Throughout most of the range of the species, but rare in the extreme north and absent from most of the Alps}.
\par 

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b hermaphroditum} (Hagerup) Böcher,{\i  Meddel. Grønl.} 147(9): 81 (1952) ({\i E. hermaphroditum} Hagerup,{\i  E. eamesii} subsp.{\i  hermaphroditum} (Hagerup) D. Löve): Flowers normally hermaphrodite, with stamens usually persistent in fruit. Stems seldom more than 50 cm, freely branched, decumbent to ascending, not rooting; leaves mostly elliptical to elliptic-oblong, 2-4 times as long as wide, often with a shallow groove beneath. 2n = 52.{\i  N. Europe, southwards to} c. 60°{\i  N., and on some of the higher mountains further south.}
